# **Mail Header Injection**

# Mail Header Injection is a vulnerability where user input is inserted into email headers (like To, Subject, CC, BCC) without proper validation. 
# Attackers inject newline characters to add new headers or even modify the message.


## Step 1
# Login to bWAPP and got Mail header injection and set the severity to  `low`
# In the input fields add Name, email and subject. 
# Once the details are added send the request to Burpsuite.
# In Burpsuite add %0ABcc: attacker2@email.com to the email. 

# **%0A** is a line feed which moves the text to next line. you can directly add &bcc: emailaddress

# you will receive a response as the email has been sent. 

# Now the attacker receives a copy of every email.


## Step 2 
# Set the severity to Medium 
# Now try inserting BCC or CC email address as %0ABCC=attacker2@email.com
# Refelects error message as `Enter a valid e-mail address!` 
# This shows that the app has blocked new line characters and header keywords 
# lets try to decode the email and try inserting the email 

# In medium level we are able to send the email by adding Test%0D%0ABcc: attacker@test.com in the remarks. Set the email to the valid email and we will see a message stating that the email has been sent. 
## `Remediation`
# - prevents attackers from creating new header lines by remove CRLF characters (\r\n)
- Reject the emails that contain spaces and nultiple email addresses

# At High security level, the application usually adds stronger protections against Mail Header Injection. These protections typically include:

- Email format validation
- Filtering of \r and \n characters
- Blocking encoded CRLF (%0D%0A)
- Removing header keywords like bcc: or cc:
